Addressing the gender gap requires both structural changes and cultural shifts. First, institutions must implement transparent hiring practices and bias training to ensure that qualified women are not overlooked. Second, funding agencies should consider equity metrics in grant evaluations—rewarding collaborative projects that include diverse teams. Third, mentorship programs tailored for women and LGBTQ+ scientists can help bridge the experience gap; I recall the support of a senior researcher who guided me through my first publication, proving that a single mentor can alter career trajectories. Finally, educational curricula at all levels must weave gender equity into science topics, normalizing the presence of women scientists in history lessons and laboratory exercises.

